Hypocrystalline, vesicular sample of Dome C (1964 dome).  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and minor olivine and Fe-Ti oxides in a glassy groundmass containing sparse plagioclase microlites.  Crystal clots of plagioclase, pyroxenes, and Fe-Ti oxides are common and groundmass glass exhibits flow textures.
Sample of Dome C (1964 dome) with similar mineralogy and texture to 84Au-2 but lacking olivine as a phenocryst phase and having a larger proportion of vesicles

Dome A (1935) sample.  Plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and minor Fe-Ti oxide phenocrysts with a trace of skeletal olivine and opacite-rimmed hornblende in a hypocrystalline groundmass of plagioclase microlites, Fe-Ti oxides, pyroxenes, and brown interstitial glass
Dome B (1935 "tholoid").  Similar mineralogy and texture as 84Au-4 but containing a larger proportion of groundmass glass
Dome B (1935 "tholoid").  Similar mineralogy and texture as 84Au-4 but containing a larger proportion of groundmass glass
Dome B (1935 "tholoid").  Plagioclase, hypersthene, and augite phenocrysts, minor skeletal olivine with corona texture, and opacite-rimmed hornblende.  Groundmass is similar to 84Au-4.

Vesicular, glassy sample of rubble flow off the 1976 dome.  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, augite, orthopyroxene, Fe-Ti oxide, and minor olivine in a groundmass of vesicular, colorless glass containing sparse plagioclase microlites and spherulites up to 0.15 mm in diameter.

1976 rubble flow sample.  Plagioclase, orthopyroxene, augite, and Fe-Ti oxide phenocrysts in a vesicular glassy matrix containing sparse plagioclase microlites and abundant flow textures.  Olivine is present in trace amounts surrounded by an intergrowth of fine-grained pyroxene+plagioclase+Fe-Ti oxides.

1976 rubble flow sample.  Plagioclase, orthopyroxene, augite, and Fe-Ti oxide phenocrysts in a vesicular glassy matrix containing sparse plagioclase microlites and abundant flow textures.  Olivine is present in trace amounts surrounded by an intergrowth of fine-grained pyroxene+plagioclase+Fe-Ti oxides.

Sample of 1976 dome.  Plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, Cr-spinel bearing olivine, and Fe-Ti oxides phenocrysts in a groundmass composed of plagioclase microlites, minor pyroxenes, and Fe-Ti oxides with a trace of clear interstitial glass. Olivine is oxidized along fractures and is rimmed by fine grained plagioclase+opaque phases+pyroxene.  Hornblende occurs as rare small (0.05 mm) inclusions in olivine.

Hypocrystalline sample of 1976 dome.  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and Fe-Ti oxide in a clear glassy groundmass showing a large degree of vesicularity and flow texturing.  Olivine is present as a single grain in the center of a clot of opaque+hypersthene+plagioclase, possibly in reaction relation.

Hypocrystalline sample of 1976 dome.  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and Fe-Ti oxide in a clear glassy groundmass showing a large degree of vesicularity and flow texturing.  Olivine is present as a single grain in the center of a clot of opaque+hypersthene+plagioclase, possibly in reaction relation.

Hypocrystalline sample of 1976 dome.  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and Fe-Ti oxide in a clear glassy groundmass showing a large degree of vesicularity and flow texturing.  Olivine is present as a single grain in the center of a clot of opaque+hypersthene+plagioclase, possibly in reaction relation.

Dome C (1964) sample. Plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, and trace olivine and hornblende phenocrysts in a holocrystalline groundmass of plagioclase microlites, pyroxene, and Fe-Ti oxide.  Olivine sometimes shows a faint reaction rim or occurs in the center of Fe-Ti oxide+plagioclase+pyroxene intergrowths. Hypersthene is slightly oxidized along fractures.

Random boulder in historic debris flow (possibly 1812).  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, olivine, and Fe-Ti oxide in a massive, holocrystalline groundmass of plagioclase microlites, Fe-Ti oxides, and pyroxenes.  Olivine shows faint reaction rims of fine-grained Fe-Ti oxides+pyroxenes+plagioclase

Random boulder in historic debris flow (possibly 1812).  Plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, olivine, and Fe-Ti oxide phenocrysts in a groundmass of plagioclase microlites, pyroxenes, and Fe-Ti oxides.  Olivine contains Cr-spinel, is rounded, and shows faint reaction rims of fine grained pyroxene and plagioclase

Boulder in lobate rubble flow (possibly 1883).  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, olivine, and Fe-Ti oxides, and pyroxenes.  Olivine is altering to serpentine (?) along fractures and is surrounded by reaction rims of either fine grained plagioclase+pyroxene or intergrown Fe-Ti oxide+pyroxene

Boulder in lobate rubble flow (possibly 1883).  Phenocrysts of plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, olivine, and Fe-Ti oxides, and pyroxenes.  Olivine is altering to serpentine (?) along fractures and is surrounded by reaction rims of either fine grained plagioclase+pyroxene or intergrown Fe-Ti oxide+pyroxene

Sample from short lava flow, possibly 1883.  Plagioclase, hypersthene, augite, olivine, and relict hornblende phenocrysts in a holocrystalline groundmass of plagioclase microlites, pyroxenes, and Fe-Ti oxides.  Hornblende is completely recrystallized to fine-grained Fe-Ti oxide+plagioclase+pyroxene.  Olivine is surrounded by a faint dusty rim.  Groundmass contains lighter patches or bands with similar mineralogy to the rest of the groundmass but having a smaller proportion of Fe-Ti oxide.

Felsic portion of a large piece of banded scoria, total initial sample weight 5 kg.  15% light colored bands, 85% dark colored bands.  Light bands up to 2 cm thick, hosted in the dark portions. The light portion is 15% gray throughout, with a very minor pinkish tinge on the outsides.  20% plagioclase, 1-3mm; <5% pyroxene 0.5 to 1mm; very light gray microcrystalline groundmass with abundant angular and irregular voids down to <<1 mm.

Mafic portion of a large piece of banded scoria, total initial sample weight 5 kg.  15% light colored bands, 85% dark colored bands.  Light bands up to 2 cm thick, hosted in the dark portions.  Light bands shear down to sub-mm streaks (smaller than individual phenocrysts), possible sub-macroscopic mingling.  The dark portion is 45% gray on the outside of the block and 85% gray in the interior; very similar to 06AUMC005a and 06AUMC007c.
12x11x9 cm 1.6kg irregular, 5-sided column fragment.  40% gray throughout.  Estimated plagioclase:pyroxene ratio of 65:35.

column13: 1906 lava?  Medium dark-gray (N4) hypersthene basalt, porphyritic, with vesicular structure.  Plagioclase phenocrysts range in size from 0.1 to 3 mm.  The median composition is An[58?], but one rounded grain of anorthite (average index 1.58) was seen as presumed to be a xenocryst.  The salite crystals have nY 1.70, suggesting a composition about Ca50Mg30Fe20.  The hypersthene prisms, which range in size from 0.1 to 1 mm, have nZ 1.70 corresponding to En73Fs27.  The optic axial angle of the olivine seen in thin section was the same as that in 46AC97, suggesting that here also its composition is about Fo72Fa28.  Olivine is rare, and no olivine was found in the crushed fragments.  The groundmass consists of plagioclase laths and augite rods in brown glass with an index of 1.50 plus/minus 0.005.  The accessory minerals are magnetite or ilmenite, from 1 to 0.1 mm, and apatite, in stubby prisms, 0.05 mm long, clear where included in hypersthene or salite but with a slightly pseudodichroic rim elsewhere.

column12: From the eastern margin of the 1986 lava flow

Matrix is similar to 86Au101 [Matrix contains zones of microcrystalline (plag-px-ox) groundmass juxtaposed with microlite-free, colorless glass].

Lava flow phase.  Very dark gray, streaked sample of the 1986 lava flow.  Contains phenocrysts of plag, opx, cpx, oxides, ol (mostly skeletal), and a trace amount of ragged, brown hornblende.  Matrix is similar to 86Au110 but contains a higher proportion of glass.

Dome building phase.  Gray, dense fragment of 1986 lava dome collected as an incandescent block.  Phenocryst mineralogy is plag, opx, cpx, exsolved oxides, and trace resorbed ol.  Matrix is microcrystalline with rare pools of clear, colorless glass.

column12: Kaguyak. near Big River narrows, high on right bank, other side of nose from Y-125
column13: Kaguyak Ignimbrite. Dark grey-brown ignimbrite with a sandy matrix and abundant small dacite pumice clasts; includes at least one PCZ in upper part of the section; Conspicuous 2-m-thick LCZ near top of section (same as Y-125 LCZ). Ignimbrite+underlying fallout rest on Big Breccia deposit. Exposed thickness: 12 m. PCZs: one well-developed and several faint ones. See text for MP and ML. Pumice clasts: white pumice, coarsely vesicular, many large pxn-clot blebs. Lithic clasts: all lithics are andesite-dacite lava clasts; many have orange-brown alteration rinds.
Coarse dacite pumice lapilli; angular fallout mixed w/brown soil; not quite primary. Exposed thickness >45 cm (base not exposed). See text for MP. No lithics seen.

column12: Kaguyak. above right bank of Big River, near narrows; north of caldera rim
column13: Kaguyak. intact fall beneath ignimbrite, which in turn overlies the Big Breccia deposit. Fallout is lithic-rich, very coarse sand +granules +lapilli (to 2.5 cm) in the basal 1-2 cm, and medium with some coarse sand in top 1 cm. Exposed thickness 2-3 m. Pumice clasts: buff pumice; very few pxn-clot blebs; texture finer, more evenly vesicular than ignimbrite pumice.

column12: Kaguyak. Saddle between Eastern Edifice and Dome 2315
column13: Lithic-rich lapilli fall beneath ignimbrite; lapilli layer has ~1mm of tan silt at its base. Exposed thickness 3 to 13 cm. Pumice clasts: very few pxn-clot blebs; white, buff, and plenty of grey pumice. [Note: text refers to both this sample and another at the same location as both "Y-131". For clarity, GeoDIVA has added an "_a" to the end of this sample name.]

column12: Kaguyak. Jn mesa at 1450' elevation, NW of Big River
column13: Veneer of ignimbrite thinning to 30 cm, overlies fallout; fallout probably shaved by ignimbrite. Exposed thickness: 9 cm. Pumice clasts: white to buff, some grey; most are bleb-poor, but pumice with blebs is present.

Coarse pumice fall, base not found; ignimbrite remnant preserved nearby, but is not in direct contact with fallout at this location. Exposed thickness >80 cm. Pumice clasts: grey, white, cream, some banded; some are nearly bleb-free, others are full of pxn clot blebs.

column11: Mt Churchill White River East Lobe
column13: Summit pumice; loose accumulation of light-colored pumice, ranging in size from lapilli to blocks as much as 50 cm in diameter. Scattered throughout these tephra deposits, and locally abundant, are angular to subangular clasts of a variety of volcanic rocks, chiefly dark-colored, porphyritic and aphyric andesitic lava, and an occasional block of granitic rock and chlorite-rich amygdaloidal lava. The lithic fragments are similar in size to the pumice fragments and are interpreted to be rock ripped from the vent conduit walls during the explosive eruption(s). Also scattered throughout the tephra are clasts of yellow-orange pumice and lithics that apparently have been hydrothermally altered. Underlying this loose surface layer of pumice and lithic debris is a frozen zone of bedded tephra, consisting of pumice lapilli and blocks and exotic rock fragments disseminated in an ash matrix. White River Ash.

plagioclase from 2008 gabbro. From the 38x35x23 cm block described above.  Well developed mineralogical layering w/ "anorthosite" up to 4 cm thick and thicker hb-rich layers. Extremely friable block -- separated b3 into individual crystals with fingertip pressure! There are 4 domains within this sample, fragments of each were handpicked for analysis.  (1) 09KCnye012b1 is anorthosite, w plag ~3mm.  (2) 09KCnye012b2 is coarse amphibole gabbro w amphibole to 1.5cm, plag to 7mm, and CI ~80.  (3) 09KCnye012b3 is moderately coarse gabbro w/ amph to 5mm, plag to 4mm, and CI~50.  (01), (02), and (03) are subparallel.  (4) 09KCnye012b4 is fine-grained px gabbro

amphibole from 2008 gabbro. 1st day back @ Kasatochi - low ceiling - lt wind.  Arr Adak~17:00, left ~21:00 travel overnight, @KS in morning.  Sample is 25 cm l-max piece of cumgab in slope wash.  Very hb-rich regions.  Only HB collected as "field mineral separate".  (PLANT - just uphill from nye100 - uphill from "the rock" - single sprig of plant- orthogonal 2-fold sym beach-pea-looking.  Growing from secontary mud and ash deposite at least a few, maybe several m thick.  this plant growing in "new"soil - not from uncovered '08 or pre'08 soil.). Equant 1-4mm amphibole w/ minor plag.  Analyzed as amph separate proxy by hand picking fragments as cleanly as I could.

lava lithic in '08 pgs. Single relatively dense brown pumice from lower of 2 conspicuous coarse-grained fall deposits; clots of large hb and plag. Dark gray to black, dense.  Very xl rich (>=30%plag, 20%px, x% amph.  Equigranular ~1mm.
lava lithic in '08 pgs. Single dark-gray, scoriaceous bomb from upper of 2 conspicuous coarse-grained fall deposits; scattered large hb and plag xtals. Dense, xl rich, 30%k lava.

2008 pyroclastic deposits, basaltic andesite scoria. Hornblende- and plag-bearing grey pumice clast, density 1170 kg/m3. Vesicles <2mm, euhedral hornblende and plag crystals, grey in color. Doesn't really fit into either the "brown" or "white" categories based on physical appearance. Does chemistry match? Sample wt. 20.1 g.

Lower Pumice 3-20cm thick lapilli layer, consisting of well-sorted, brown-beige pumice fragments and abundant smaller lithic fragments (23 wt% of layer). The accidental lithic ejecta of PL consist almost entirely of black, dense, vitric material.

Middle Pumice is 10-115cm thick layer of moderately well-sorted, ungraded vitric lapilli and fine blocks. The most abundant clast-type is brown-beige pumice, which occurs as lapilli and bombs as large as 15cm in the long dimension. PM also has sparse, smaller lithic fragments (5 wt% of layer) that are both vitric (60% of lithics) and vairably altered volcanic lithologies (40% of lithics)

Upper Pumice is 3-20cm thick and dark yellow-brown, a mixture of brown-beige pumice and dark gray-black scoria (42 wt% and 23 wt% of layer, respectively) and an abundance of non-vitric lithics (32 wt% of layer). Overall the PU lapilli are poorly sorted and vary in mean grain size (6-14mm) with the layer. Scoriaceous clasts are larger tha pumiceous clasts and lithic fragments (mean dia ~5mm and ~3mm, respectively). Scoriaceous bombs up to 10cm in the long dimension occur up to 10km from summit.

column13: Inferred to be a ejected volcanic block. Light gray slightly purplish, fine grained and porous groundmass, in which small feldspars and dark brown and green hornblende like crystals are readily distinguishable by the naked eye. The texture is uniform, the brown hornblende being the more variable constituent, a single crystal nearly half an inch in diameter was observed. The rock is rough to the touch and somewhat friable. Iron ore and augite are present. Apatite occurs sparingly and magnetite is present in poorly defined crystals.
